<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>C.I. Mutual Funds: Asia - TCW Asia</TITLE></HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#EBE8DF"><CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=2><TR><TD><A HREF="home2.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Mutual Funds" SRC="pagebanner_white.gif"></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><PRE></PRE><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>TCW Asia</H1><FONT SIZE=4>Shaun Chan and Frank Chiang have worked together for over 10 years charting what the World Bank calls "the Asian miracle".  It is a daunting task.  Asian markets are notably different from their western counterparts, with shorter cycles which can be driven by politics as much as by economics.<p><IMG hspace=15 WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=101 ALT="Picture of Shaun & Frank" ALIGN=right Alt=Fund Manager Pictures" SRC="images/shaun_frank.gif">Mr. Chan's background as an economist is brought to bear in the analysis of the general political and economic environment in the region, while Mr. Chiang's stockpicking skills and instincts are invaluable in making trading gains.<P>Both men spend considerable time visiting the portfolio holdings to monitor progress and ensure that investors continue to receive the best value for their investment dollar.</FONT><BR clear=all><PRE></PRE><HR NOSHADE><FONT SIZE=5>Advisers to:</FONT><P><B><A HREF="tcw_asia_pacific.html">C.I. Pacific Fund</A><P><A HREF="prices.html">Daily Fund Price update</A><P></B><PRE></PRE><BR><HR NOSHADE><FONT SIZE=5>Comments</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=4><EM>As at July 31, 1996</EM><P>The Asian market weakened significantly this July affected by bother internal and external factors. <P> The main external factor is the threat of rising US interest rates. This reduces the attractiveness of holding equities and prompts Asian economies to also raise their rates. Although Hong Kong is the most US interest rate-sensitive market, the stimulatory effects of a reflating Chinese economy and the recovery of earnings growth helped keep the stockmarket resilient.  We are feeling more positive towards Hong Kong.  <P> The main internal factor is the slowing growth of exports.  Markets most affected were Singapore and Thailand.  Export competitiveness is failing because of the relative strength of Asian currencies and because of rising costs due to the inflation of higher wages. As a consequence, economic growth forecasts are being reduced because the trade sector is a large component of the Asian economies.  Furthermore, if imports do not slow down at the same pace, more problems will arise with higher trade deficits.  <P> We are not unduly worried because we detect two major economic trends evolving that can arrest the export problem.  The first trend is economic acceleration of the two large Asian economies, China and Japan.  Second is the synchronized global economic recovery in 1997.  These should strengthen the prospects of the exports sectors in Asia.  But the ideal long term solution is that Asian corporations should strive to improve efficiencies to be able to compete in the global market.  <P> Thailand was the worst hit this month.  The central bank has kept monetary policy tight too long.  Floods last year caused inflation which actually masked the start of a decelerating trend in the economy.  The slowdown has now become evident but interest rates cannot fall aggressively because of external deficits. We are keeping our exposure low in Thailand.  <P> Political factors hurt the Indonesian market this month, and the equity market will find it difficult to rise with the political uncertainty.  If disruptions continue, the economy could suffer, interest rates could rise to reflect rising risk premiums, and the currency could be under speculative attack.  Against this environment, it is prudent to reduce the Fund's Indonesia exposure.  <P> Asian stockmarkets may be experiencing rough moments but one should be reminded of the key strengths of Asia. It remains the fastest growing region in the world.  Region-wide infrastructure spending has been stepped up to keep the growth sustainable.  Domestic consumption has grown into sizable markets offsetting the need to export most goods. These are encouraging trends. <P></FONT><HR><center><A HREF="home2.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Home Page" SRC="menu/about_ci.gif"></A><A HREF="ditip.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Daily Investment Tip" SRC="menu/daily_tip.gif"></A><A HREF="feedback.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Feedback to C.I." SRC="menu/feedback.gif"></A><A HREF="prices.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Fund Prices" SRC="menu/daily_prices.gif"></A><A HREF="links.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Web Links" SRC="menu/links.gif"></A><P></center><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds Inc., 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="maito:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
