<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>C.I. Mutual Funds: Canada - J. Zechner Associates</TITLE></HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#EBE8DF"><CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=2><TR><TD><A HREF="home2.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Mutual Funds" SRC="pagebanner_white.gif"></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><PRE></PRE><H1 ALIGN=CENTER>J. Zechner Associates</H1><FONT SIZE=4><B>&nbsp; John Zechner</B><BR><IMG hspace=10 WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=107 ALT="Picture of John Zechner" ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/zechner.gif">Toronto native John Zechner casts an experienced eye on the Canadian economy, looking for the larger trends which could indicate the direction of movement in the country's stock and bond markets.  His portfolios are constructed of blue-chip securities which possess a high degree of liquidity, allowing him the freedom of movement necessary for pursuing growth while preserving value.<BR CLEAR=ALL><P><B>&nbsp; Steve Craig</B><BR><IMG hspace=10 WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=107 ALT="Picture of Steve Craig" ALIGN=LEFT SRC="images/craig.gif">Steve Craig is a veteran trader of the Canadian equity markets on both a retail and institutional level.  He has held senior posts with such well-known Canadian firms as Wood Gundy, Walwyn Inc., First Boston Canada Inc. and First Marathon Inc.  His responsibilities currently include equity trading as well as technical analysis and stock selection.<BR CLEAR=ALL><P></FONT><PRE></PRE><HR NOSHADE><FONT SIZE=5>Adviser to:</FONT><P><B><A HREF="zech_growth.html">C.I. Canadian Growth Fund</A><BR><A HREF="zech_balanced.html">C.I. Canadian Balanced Fund</A><BR><A HREF="zech_bond.html">C.I. Canadian Bond Fund</A><BR><A HREF="zech_income.html">C.I. Canadian Income Fund</A><BR><A HREF="zech_money.html">C.I. Money Market Fund</A><br><A HREF="zech_money.html">C.I. US Money Market Fund</A><P><A HREF="prices.html">Daily Fund Price update</A><P></B><PRE></PRE><BR><HR NOSHADE><FONT SIZE=5>Comments</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=4><EM>As at July 31, 1996</EM><P><UL><LI>Stock markets were extremely volatile again in July with significant weakness mid-month followed by rallies towards month's end.  The key question continues to be the direction of interest rates over the next few months with the market shifting as each number gets reported.<P><LI>The TSE 300 declined over 2% in July following a decline of over 3% in June.  The blue chip stocks were the only area of strength as bank and utility stocks gave investors a greater feeling of comfort.  In the U.S., the differences were even more pronounced as the Dow Industrials dropped over 2%. The more broadly-based S&P 500 declined almost 5% and the technology-heavy Nasdaq index fell about 10%.  Industrial products and transport stocks suffered the biggest declines in the Canadian market. <P><LI>Bond prices did slightly better during July as bond yields dropped late in the month due to an absence of inflation.  Canadian bonds out performed their U.S. counterparts as Canadian short term interest rates were again reduced by a quarter point.  Canadian trade numbers also showed a record trade surplus for June and foreign investment in Canada showed another increase.<P><LI>Corporate earnings for the second quarter were pretty much in line with expectations, although some of the larger technology companies such as Intel, Microsoft, and IBM did better than expected.  Lower commodity prices did lead to lower earnings from the paper and base metals sectors, but this had been generally expected.  <P><LI>Declines in the market over the last few months have been fairly broadly based while the "up days" have been confined to the larger, blue chip stocks. This is a somewhat negative indicator for the months ahead since this "negative breadth" has generally occurred prior to downturns in stock prices.  However, stocks in Canada are not over-valued by historical standards, suggesting that any downturns in stock prices would not be significant. <P><LI>Economic data to be released early in August should determine whether or not the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates at its meeting on August 20.  Our expectation is that economic growth is still relatively strong in North America and that interest rates will go higher in the second half of 1996.     <P></UL></FONT><HR><center><A HREF="home2.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Home Page" SRC="menu/about_ci.gif"></A><A HREF="ditip.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Daily Investment Tip" SRC="menu/daily_tip.gif"></A><A HREF="feedback.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Feedback to C.I." SRC="menu/feedback.gif"></A><A HREF="prices.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="C.I. Fund Prices" SRC="menu/daily_prices.gif"></A><A HREF="links.html"><IMG WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=49 BORDER=0 ALT="Web Links" SRC="menu/links.gif"></A><P></center><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds Inc., 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
