<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>With RSP's,  risk is a four letter word.</H3>
Depending on your age and income, high risk investments can be appropriate.  But rarely should you use RSP funds for speculation. RSP's should be managed conservatively; after all, they are your retirement funds and they're not replaceable.  If you use RSP funds to buy, for example, a speculative stock, you're set up for a double loss_not just your money, but also the tax relief which accompanies unsheltered investment duds.  And you can't replenish losses within your RSP. So, along with the loss goes the opportunity to reap the tax deferral your money would have earned in the years until retirement.  And, don't overlook the tax value of investment losses.  You can use them against capital gains to offset the tax bill.  So avoid high risk RSP-funded investments.  They can be far more costly than you think. <p>
<p>
<p>
