<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>The crazy concern over interest rates</H3>
It seems that our day-to-day existence hangs on the vague utterances of Alan Greenspan, chairman of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board - and whether financial experts think he wants to hold or raise interest rates.  Now the Fed has done a great job of keeping inflation in check and bringing rates down.  But if Greenspan is going to do any tweaking to keep inflation in check - and so far, there's no sign of that - surely a one or two percent increase in rates from where they stand today - will not doom society as we know it.  We won't be selling the house and moving back to a mud hut.  A well-run corporation with a borrowing cost of 7 percent doesn't turn into a loser when borrowing costs go to 8 or 9 percent.   That's no reason to dump its stock.   Alan Greenspan is very bright and much-admired, but there are many better ways to determine good investment value than the way the Fed Chairman tweaks his brow and rubs his chin at appearances before the Senate Banking Committee. <p>
<p>
