een increased from $1500 to $2000 annually.   And the lifetime limit is up from $31,000 to $42,000.<P>RESP (Registered Education Savings Plan) contributions - unlike RSPs - are not tax deductible when you make them.  However, once the money is in the RESP, it grows tax free.  And the student pays the tax  - likely at a much lower rate - when the money is withdrawn for education.  The education deduction that a student can claim is also up, to one hundred dollars a month.  <P>While all of this is welcome, it is offset by rising tuition fees, making an RESP an even better idea.<P><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
