s, insurance agents.  But that's all changing because people want a more unified approach to their money management, which is what a financial adviser provides.<p>As your assets accumulate, you'll want an adviser who can put together a plan that makes sense for you.  It's your future so choose wisely.  Don't just go to an old school friend who got into the financial business, and don't sign on with anyone who makes grandiose promises, or who spends more time talking than listening.<p>The Canadian Association of Financial Planners has a roster of members and a helpful brochure called A Consumer Guide to Financial Planning, available by calling 416-593-6592. It contains details on the services provided by financial planners and the questions to ask in selecting one.<p>Or, ask your friends for references and meet with a few planners. If you shop around and ask lots of questions, you'll find a financial adviser who can help you develop an investment strategy that is right for you.<p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
