way is, in fact, an interest-free loan you gave the government for a year.  There are alternatives which can boost your cash flow and keep money in your hands instead of Ottawa's.  One way is to update the TD-1 form on file with your employer.  It determines your level of tax deduction at source.  Another way is to file a tax waiver request with Revenue Canada.  This allows you to have deductions lowered by your employer to reflect items such as RSP contributions, alimony and child support payments.When Revenue Canada approves the request, they'll notify your employer to reduce the tax bite on your paycheque.  You'll no longer get that fat refund cheque, but you will have more money throughout the year and you'll be earning the interest.  Yes, even bureaucracy is part of how MoneyWorks!  I'm Everett Banning</H3><p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
