 surprise you.  The cost of an infant for a year is about nine-and-a-half thousand dollars.  When children start kindergarten, the cost drops to below nine thousand dollars, because there is a little less day care to pay for.  At age twelve, costs slip to around seven thousand, since the need for daycare is gone.  The annual cost of a child stays in the seven thousand dollar range through the teens.  It means the cash outlay for parents is about 150 thousand dollars to raise a child.  <p><p>If you'd been able to put that in other investments, you could have a nest egg of half a million dollars.  It's a fascinating calculation, but we'll pass on that investment opportunity, for the satisfaction of watching a son or daughter take their place in our world.<p><p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
