<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>If you're short of cash, you still pay into an RSP!</H3>
The way to invest in your RSP without making a cash contribution is to open a self-directed plan. Then, you make "contributions in kind".  This means, that instead of dollars and cents, you contribute investments you already own.  For example, you may have some stocks and bonds, T-bills, mutual fund units or Savings Bonds in your safety deposit box.  Sure, they're making money for you - but they're also increasing your tax burden.  The smart thing to do, may be to put them into your RSP, where earnings are shielded from the taxes.  Instead of waiting until next year's deadline, invest your current holdings in a self-directed RSP as soon as you like.<p>
If your have cash at a later date,  you can buy back your  "contributions in kind".  Talk to a financial advisor about the flexibility of self-directed RSPs and the advantages of making "contributions in kind", because that's how Moneyworks!<p>
<p>
<p>
