The temptation is always to stay in as long as you can, then hope that you're fast enough to avoid a market slide.  <P>But the smart folks know that they won't get the timing right.   So, they diversify by putting their investments in different things.   One choice is equity funds for capital appreciation; either blue chip investments that might be less vulnerable to swings in the market or growth stocks that might see a big increase in value over the long term.  <P>Another alternative is bonds and bond funds for income.  If you believe interest rates will continue to edge downward, favour longer term bonds.  Shorter term bonds fluctuate less, and are good for preserving your capital.  <P>You can also diversify geographically. Foreign investments can both spread the risk and participate in performance. After all, Canada is only 2% of world markets, and we seldom lead in performance.<P>Talk to your investment advisor about diversifying - and sleep better at night despite volatile markets.<P><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
