and could be part of a well-diversified portfolio. The advantage of a bond mutual fund is professional management, as well as lower commissions and higher yields because fund managers buy bonds in bulk.<p><p>The usual investments for bond funds are high-quality corporate and government bonds, high-yielding preferred shares and mortgages. Bond funds tend to have low variability and generate a steady stream of income which can be re-invested or withdrawn. It is generally recommended that investors hold their bond fund as an RRSP investment because interest is fully taxed outside an RRSP. <p><p>When interest rates are on the rise, bond funds decline in price, although the interest is still paid. For this reason, bond funds are usually held as long-term investments. As well, an increasing portion of a portfolio is usually committed to bonds as an investor grows older and is looking for steady income and preservation of capital.<p><p>Don't overlook bond funds, they can have a place in every investor's portfolio.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
