e of investing means you have more hopes than plans.<P>Before you order some investment fund units, consider your needs and goals.  Will you need the money five years from now, or 25 years away?.   Do you want growth, or an income, or a bit of both?<P>Most people discover that a smart mix of investment funds suits their needs best.  Buy some meat and potatoes growth funds, with solid, long-term appreciation.  You might add a little hot pepper with an emerging markets or niche industry fund; more volatile, but offering better long term opportunities.  A bond fund can balance the ups and downs of your equity funds.  And an income or money market fund can provide more stability over the short term.<P>The key is not to own just different funds, but different kinds of funds that help achieve your goals. Ask you financial advisor about the kinds of funds that are best for you.<P><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
