his created 14 and 16 per cent mortgage rates.  Now, as they look at retirement in 20 years, there may be no government pensions because the baby boom will produce eight times more retirees than there were a generation ago. <p><p>Clearly, boomers cannot count on their houses, fixed interest rate investments, or government for their retirement income.  Economist Bill Sterling, of the money management firm BEA Associates in New York, says the boomers' demand for retirement income will provide many more years of solid growth in the stock markets, and he sees international investments as the logical way to generate the earnings people will want.  <p><p>First, he says growing demand for quality stocks and bonds will sustain a long term, positive price trend.  Second, the portion of personal wealth held in stocks and bonds has a long way to grow before it reaches historical levels.  Third, solid, long term growth is expected in Asia, Europe and parts of Latin America-all worth keeping in mind for those wanting a solid income from their assets in the years ahead.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
