<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Be wary of the IPO hotshots.</H3>
In the money business, they call them IPOs - Initial Public Offerings.  An IPO is a new stock issue, a company that was owned privately that has now made a share of its ownership available to the general public.  A new stock issue is brought onto the market by an investment dealer or a syndicate of dealers, who help set a fair price for the new stock.  In many cases, investors find IPOs very exciting, as we've seen in recent months in the high technology and natural resource sectors.  This past April and May, the average value of an IPO in New York jumped up 25 percent on the first day of public trading.  That's big money  - if you know what you're doing and if you're lucky.  But since the heydey of last spring, IPO fever has cooled, as it inevitably does.  People have lost big money too.  If you're trying to build for your future, invest in stocks that you understand and that demonstrate good value.  Wait for the new stocks to settle down. <p>
<p>
<p>
