<area coords="565,137,654,160"href="/links.html">
<area coords="22,33,98,114"href="/about_ci.html">
<area coords="240,32,316,115"href="/about_hansberger.html">
<area coords="468,26,538,115"href="/about_sector.html">
</map>
</CENTER><BR><BR>
<TD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=7>C.I. Daily $ Tip</FONT><br>By Everett Banning, Host of Moneyworks</CENTER></td>
</tr>
</table>
<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>The temptations of credit and debt.</H3>
It's so tempting to order more credit cards for your wallet.  Everybody seems to be offering us new cards these days, even the airlines and car makers.  You might feel good about having a lot of cards, but even if you don't use them, a lot of cards don't look good on a credit record.  When applying for something really important, like a  mortgage, all these cards show up on the credit check, and that might not look so good.  Anyway, take the temptation away, and you won't spend your way to trouble.  Carry just one or two cards, it's probably all you need.  Keep the credit limit down, to keep a lid on borrowing.  Use a charge card instead of a credit card, the kind that forces you to pay off the whole balance every month.  Keep written records of your card purchases, so the interest payments are added to the cost of the things you bought.  Then you'll see the real cost of temptation. <p>
<p>
<p>
