 smart to draft a loan agreement.  It may seem difficult if they ask, "What!, don't you trust me?",   but it's not a matter of trust.  Its just good common sense, because memories fade over time, and each of you may have a different impression of your original agreement.  Put it on paper.  If the loan is not repaid when expected, emotions could flare, and you don't want to lose a friend or create a rift in your family over a loan.  If you provide money to a child who's getting married, a loan agreement can ensure the money is not divided with the child's spouse in the event that the marriage doesn't last.  As well, a loan agreement might be valuable at tax time, either because you have to report the interest income, or because the interest payments can be deducted by the borrower.  So, write down the terms for everyone's sake. Even with the best of intentions, don't forget how money can bring us together and drive us apart</H3><p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
