<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>The real car thief may be the car.</H3>
Without denying yourself the pleasures and conveniences of having a car, there are some things to keep in mind that could save you money.  Remember, the cost of owning and operating a car is the biggest financial item in the budget of people under thirty.  You can get going on the other priorities of life earlier, by managing your car costs.  First, find out what the insurance will cost.  You might shop around for something that's cheaper to insure, because insurance can be more than the car payments.  Second, consider a car that uses low octane gas.  That can save hundreds of dollars a year.  Third, compare the cost of replacement parts, before you buy.  A cheap car can be very costly to repair.  Fourth, get the dealer to map out clearly all the costs of buying or leasing the car.  The interest, taxes, and other charges can be much more than you expected.<p>
<p>
<p>
