 The newly announced cuts to the OAS and GIS will provide just crumbs for the number of baby boomers now in their 30s, 40s, and 50s who are planning for their retirement years.  <P>The key to understanding the Federal government pension system is knowing how it actually works.  Money deducted from your pay for Canada Pension Payments isn't stored in some safe place, just for you.  It goes right out of the treasury to support those who now collect pensions.  <P>As the number of pension recipients grows and the comparative number of workers who pay into the system shrinks, the need to make your own independent plans for your later years is more evident. Saving may not be enough, we will all probably have to consider investing to make our money grow.<P>All of this points to the wisdom of careful financial planning for baby boomers over the next years to avoid any nasty retirement surprises.<P><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
