ur pension plan administrator.<p><p>What kind of pension plan do you have? The most common, a defined benefit plan, will pay you a specified pension based on your years of service and your employment earnings. A different kind of pension plan, a money purchase plan, keeps separate records for each employee based on the amount contributed. The money is invested and, at retirement, the employee is paid a proportional amount based on the amount of contributions and the success of the plan's investments.<p><p>Is your pension plan indexed to inflation? If not, you could fall behind over time. Will your spouse receive your pension benefits if you die? Can you take your pension with you if you leave the company? Are you allowed to transfer your pension into an RRSP? Don't wait until retirement to find the flaws in your pension plan.<p><p>Also, save for your retirement by making the maximum contribution to your own RRSP, and by investing in stocks, bonds, or an investment fund outside an RRSP. If you do, they will really be your golden years.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
