 are closer relations to speculative stocks than long-term investments.<p><p>Managers of these flashy funds may buy and sell constantly, hoping to time short-term market movements. When they win, they win big. When they lose, the losses are just as great, plus they pass along all those sales commissions to the fund investors.<p><p>A less volatile fund management approach is based on solid research and buying established companies which lead their sectors or which show underlying value for the long term. The gains won't be as spectacular, but then neither will the crashes. Over the long term, you might come out ahead.<p><p>Be sure you read the prospectus of a mutual fund to learn about the investment objectives and level of risk. Ask your investment adviser about long-term and short-term strategies. You may want to invest a small amount with a risky fund, but you will probably be better off looking for managers who are in it for the long haul.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
