k into your bank feeling submissive. Remember, you are shopping for a service and you deserve to be treated as a customer.  In a loan interview, do bring a list of your assets and liabilities, your sources of income, and your basic expenses.  Do tell the bank why you want the money.  The loan rate you pay is partly determined by your financial history, your assets, and your use of the money.  After satisfying your banker's needs, do some probing yourself.  Ask for the best loan rate possible and for options such as early payment provisions.  Do remember that this is a business transaction.  It's good to build a long term relationship with your bank, but remember that it has to be a winning transaction for you, too.Be prepared to shop around for a lower rate or better payment terms. Remember, when you are borrowing you're giving the bank your business, not asking for a favour</H3><p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
