<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>What about the price of your house?</H3>
It's been said so often, that a house is the biggest investment a person makes in their lifetime, although your retirement savings plan will likely be larger.  Experts advise that you not use your house as your only investment, because, like everything else, it is subject to the ups and downs of the marketplace:  Those who bought houses in the hot Toronto market in the late 1980s have seen values down about 25 percent.  In Vancouver, houses bought in the late 1980s, kept rising, by about 35 percent.  Values are down in the Maritimes and Quebec, up in Alberta.  Like the stock market, the house market rises and falls on supply and demand.  By monitoring economic and political developments, and watching trends in society - like retirees choosing the west coast - you can analyze your house investment, and keep it in perspective as part of your basket of assets.  But remember, a house is also your home, and that represents benefits that don't show up on a balance sheet. <p>
<p>
<p>
