<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>How a buyback can beat a dividend.</H3>
The usual way for a company to pass along improved profits to shareholders is through a higher dividend.  But some companies, especially those in cyclical industries, are hesitant to raise the dividend for fear of creating an ongoing cost or risking a future dividend cut.  Some companies pile up the cash.  But that can provoke shareholders to agitate for their reward.  In response, a company will occasionally announce plans to buy up some of its own shares in the market.  Just the announcement of a share buyback will usually move a stock up - and even higher when the buyback actually happens. In the eighties, shares in U.S. companies beat the market by more than ten percent in the four years following a share buyback program.  So, buy the companies that buy themselves... because that's how MoneyWorks! <p>
<p>
