r cent.  Because percentages are made up of apples, oranges and grapefruit, we have to know what we are comparing.  <p><p>Try this simple example.  Let's say I have $500 to my name.  If I lose half of it, $250, my assets have gone down 50 per cent in one year. Next year, I earn back my money and I have $500 again. But it didn't go back up 50 per cent, it went up 100 per cent.  Still, I've only got $500.<p> <p>Simple stuff, but valuable when you examine the performance reports attached to any investment you're considering.  A huge one-year increase may not be that impressive after all.  Depending on your investment goals, it may be better to go for less volatile, year-after-year growth than the big percentages. Ask your financial adviser what investments are best for you.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
