e date, however, the interest mounts rapidly.  A typical taxpayer would have to earn almost 27% on a GIC to keep pace with credit card interest charges.<p><p>Avoid the perils of plastic by using just one card, even though you will constantly be offered other cards by companies wanting to earn their 27% from you. Additional cards become part of the pool of credit extended to you, even if they have a zero balance, and a financial institution will take them into account when you apply for a loan or a mortgage.<p><p>One card, one monthly statement, and one payment in full is the smart way to corral your cards. Then you can invest your money instead of paying it out on credit card interest.<p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
