ibute to the lower earning spouse's RRSP.  The higher earning spouse gets the tax deduction.  Although you can't claim more than your RRSP limits, the benefits of this strategy come in later years.<p><p>The goal in your later years should be to have both spouses earning almost the same income.  That way, both of you are in the lowest possible tax brackets.  Here's how you work towards that goal. Spousal RRSP contributions become the property, and later the income, of the lower earning spouse.  When planned properly, by taking into account other sources of retirement income, both of you should be earning about the same -- thereby splitting the tax load in your retirement years. Talk to your investment adviser about Spousal RRSP's.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
