nancial adviser or stay with a bond investment fund before plunging in too deeply.<p><p>Bonds are issued with maturity dates commonly ranging from three months to 30 years and with a fixed interest rate. Because bonds are traded and their prices vary over time, you can receive a capital gain or loss as well as the interest. When other interest rates rise, bonds become less attractive and their prices fall. When interest rates are falling, bonds are king.<p><p>The price variance is related to the length of maturity. A 2% change in interest rates will change the price of a three-year bond about 5%; a 10-year bond will change 12%; a 30-year bond about 18%.<p><p>Big changes for supposedly dull old bonds.<p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
