<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Bonds are not always safe investments.</H3>
There are both risks and rewards to bonds.  When a government or business wants to borrow money, it issues a bond, a piece of paper that is simply a promise by the borrower to pay back the money, with interest, by a fixed date. That can be two or three years from now - or thirty years from now.  But that's where the risk comes in.  If the interest rate on the bond is 7 percent, and rates in the marketplace rise to 10 percent, the face value of your 7 percent bond will be discounted to make up for the lower interest rate.  This is also important if you invested in a long term bond fund.  When interest rates look like they may go higher, consider short term bonds and bond funds. If rates might go lower, then longer term is wise - because bonds may go up in value.  So, watch interest rate trends when considering bond investments. <p>
<p>
<p>
