hase cost, all improvements turn into profits.<p><p>Try dollar cost averaging - investing the same amount weekly or monthly. When markets are low, you will buy more shares; when markets are high, you will buy fewer. It's like waiting for the Boxing Day sales.<p><p>Your chance of losing on a stock pick in one year is about 30%. But over 10 years, the chance of losing drops to just 4%. Over the last 60 years, stock investments have returned, on average, about 10% per year, better than any other investment.  If you put a fixed amount into stocks regularly, you will build up a sizable nest egg while diminishing the effects of stock volatility.<p><p>Whether it's mutual funds or individual stocks - slow but sure wins the race.<p><p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
