ncome.   Each affects demand in the marketplace, and demand determines pricing. <P>On both points, these factors suggest housing prices will stay flat for much of the decade. First, since the mid-1960s, the birthrate has fallen. There are fewer home buyers following on the heels of the baby boom. That shrinking demand means that a 1980s-style housing boom is unlikely for many years . <P>Second, wage gains have not kept pace with housing prices.  That has reduced housing demand.  You should not view home ownership as an investment -- see a house as something you buy to live in, not to make money on.<P><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
