<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Avoid getting burned by  "flash-in-the-pan" funds </H3>
Watch out for flash-in-the-pan investment funds. Such funds often have one or two years of spectacular results. They get lots of attention. And then they plummet,  taking investors with them. Managers of these funds practice what is called "market timing". They buy and sell stocks a lot, hoping to time short-term price movements. When they win, they win big. But when the bubble bursts, they crash. An opposite approach is based upon solid long term stock selection. It focuses on knowing the company, recognizing value and growth opportunities, then, hanging in for the long haul until the market recognizes that value. In the short term, the market timers beat the stock pickers. But in the long term, the research-focused approach of stock pickers always does better. So when you're buying a mutual fund, look for those that are in it for the long haul. <p>
<p>
<p>
