<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Is it time for defence, or offence?</H3>
The roller coaster behaviour of the markets recently has various experts talking about either a defensive or an offensive strategy.  Do you put your money into investments that will protect your capital through volatile times, or do you look for new opportunities that might put you far ahead?  Perhaps the solution lies in doing a bit of both.  On the defensive side, you might lower the amount you have invested in the Canadian and American stock markets.  Choose stocks that pay a good dividend, and remain solid during tough markets - like phone companies and utilities, things people spend money on no matter what's happening in the economy.  Increase the amount you have in bonds, so stocks and bonds might each be 40 or 45 percent of your portfolio.  Perhaps keep 10 or 15 percent in cash.  That gives you something for some quick offense, to buy bargains when stock prices are lower.  And stay away from fads. <p>
<p>
<p>
