<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Can you make money without taking risks?</H3>
The average investor would like to have little or no risk, and yet, make lots of money.  The problem is that investing doesn't quite work that way.  Perhaps if we change the way we view risk, we may be willing to accept it more.  Recently, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission developed a method of comparing the risk levels of various investment funds.  The method measures in up and down volatility.  Those with greater volatility were called more risky   But here's what the exercise also found:  Some of the most volatile - or supposedly more risky funds - made the most money for investors.  This is not to say that one should look for funds that rock and roll all over the charts.  It does mean that people who want to earn more should consider using a small part of their assets for investments that rise and fall in the short term and deliver better results. <p>
<p>
