igher risk that goes with potentially higher performance? Second, look at a fund's real return, including any commissions or management fees you will have to pay. Third, don't be greedy. A volatile fund can fall as quickly as it rose.<p><p>Fourth, when evaluating a fund's long-term record, look at year-over-year rather than average returns. This will tell you if an exceedingly good or bad year is skewing the average. Fifth, find out who the fund managers are and how long they've been there.<p><p>Sixth, buy from a company with multiple funds and find out the costs of switching among funds. If you ask the right questions, you stand a better chance of finding the right fund.<p><A HREF="/old_ditiplist.html"><B>Previous Tips</B></A><HR><PRE></PRE><FONT SIZE=2>This communication is published by C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. Any commentaries contained in this communication are provided as a general source of information and should not be considered personal investment advice.  Every effort has been made to ensure that the material contained in this communication is accurate at the time of publication.  However, C.I. Mutual Funds Inc. cannot guarantee its accuracy or completeness and accepts no responsibility for any loss arising from any use of or reliance on the information contained herein.<P><A HREF="disclaimer.html">Complete disclaimer text</A><p></FONT>All material on this site is copyright &copy; C.I. Mutual Funds, 1995, 1996<P>Questions?  send mail to <A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@cifunds.com">webmaster@cifunds.com</A>.</BODY> </HTML> 
