<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Here are some shares you might prefer</H3>
Preferred shares in Canadian companies can be a good way for investors to reap steady income without facing a big tax bite. They are an ideal investment outside of your RSP because they give you the benefit of a dividend tax credit. And they're usually a secure investment, because preferred share holders go to the front of the claims line in the event the company runs into trouble. And, if trouble does occur, the dividends on preferred shares keep adding up until the issuing company can make good to the holders.  In recent years the attraction to preferreds has faded because many companies that were big issuers did run into trouble.  But the benefits of holding preferred shares still remain.So look at your investments, tax picture and income needs. Avoiding a big tax bite on steady income can greatly improve how MoneyWorks!<p>
<p>
<p>
