</tr>
</table>
<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>Bonds are not always safe investments.</H3>
There are both risks and rewards to bonds.  When a government or a business wants to borrow money, it issues a bond, a piece of paper that is simply a promise by the borrower to pay back the money, with interest, by a fixed date. That can be two or three years from now - or thirty years from now.  But that's where the risk comes in.  If the interest rate on the bond is 7 percent, and rates in the marketplace rise to 10 percent, the value of your 7 percent bond will be discounted to make up for the lower interest rate.  This is important if you bought 30 years bonds which you intended to sell in 10 years.  Or, if you invested in a fund that invests in long term bonds.  When interest rates look like they may go higher, consider short term bonds and bond funds.  If interest rates look like they might go lower, then longer term is wise - because bonds may go up in value.  So, watch interest rate trends when considering bond investments. <p>
<p>
<p>
