<hr noshade><p>
<IMG Hspace=10 border=0 alt="Everett Banning" ALIGN=right SRC="/banning.jpeg">
<h3>What some of the numbers mean.</H3>
The business reports we hear on radio and TV usually include the daily fluctuations of the financial markets.  What are these numbers?  The Dow Jones average was developed a hundred years ago.  It reflects changes in the share prices of only 30 of the biggest companies on the New York Stock Exchange.  Since that can be quite a meaningless, the    S & P charts 500 companies in New York.  Even more useful to many people is the Nasdaq Index, which follows almost four thousand stocks.  In Canada, the TSE 300 follows 300 big companies listed in Toronto.  All of these indexes have some value.  For some reason, media folk always tell you the daily price of gold.  But gold prices haven't changed in ten years.  Perhaps they just give out some of these numbers without thinking whether they have any real value. <p>
<p>
<p>
