<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>SafetyPosit(sm): Key Definitions and Concepts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#E6E8FA" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<H2>Storage Management Key Definitions and Concepts</H2>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<H3>Types of Data Backup</H3>

<P>There are several types of backup which have been defined.  These include 
<B>full</B>, <B>differential</B>, <B>incremental</B>, <B>selected</B>, and 
<B>consolidation</B>.  The following defines each of these terms:</P>

<P><A NAME="1"><B>Full Backup</B></A> - A full backup includes everything 
that is in a file system.  A recent full backup allows the administrator to 
quickly rebuild a disk drive or file system from a single saveset (backup 
job).  The advantage of a full backup is that it is complete and therefore 
simplifies the restore process.  The disadvantage is that a full backup can 
take much longer to create than other types of backup and can require much 
more off-line (tape) storage.<BR><CENTER>  
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><A NAME="2"><B>Differential Backup</B></A> - this is a type of partial 
backup.  It is called differential because the backup system will 
automatically select for backup any file that has been modified since the 
last full backup.  The advantage of a differential backup is that only the 
most recent differential backup saveset is required to update the most recent 
full backup saveset.  A maximum of two savesets covers any restore 
situation.  The disadvantage is that differential backups jobs grow with each 
successive partial backup until a new full backup is performed.  At some 
point a differential backup may require and excessive amount of time or 
off-line storage.<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><A NAME="3"><B>Incremental Backup</B></A> - this is a type of partial 
backup.  It is called incremental because it only backs up files that have 
changed since the last full or partial backup.  The advantage is that 
incremental backup schemes are the fastest to run and require the least 
amount of off-line storage since only recently modified files are included.  
A possible disadvantage is that a full restore of a file system may require 
the application of many layers of backup jobs (savesets).  Good restore 
software and an automated off-line storage can negate this disadvantage by 
making restores from multiple savesets appear seamless.<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>


<P><A NAME="4"><B>Selective Backup</B></A> - users or administrators may 
want perform a backup job on demand instead of having regularly scheduled 
backups.  This is likely where file usage is sporadic.  Even then, there 
may be comfort in having a regularly scheduled backup even if it is generally 
very small.<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>


<P><A NAME="5"><B>Consolidation Backup</B></A> - a consolidation backup 
is an alternative to a full backup for protecting an organization's critical 
data.  In some instances, there may be many files that never change and 
therefore it does not make sense to include them in each full backup.  In 
this case the static data can be backed up once to both local and off-site 
storage and then never backed up again until something changes.  Most static 
data consists of operating system and application files.  Even within 
operating system and application directories, there may be critical 
configuration or directory files that do need frequent backup.  Good backup 
software will find all files that change and backup them up in  a 
consolidation backup.  Running a consolidation backup on a weekly or monthly 
basis can reduce the number of incremental backups that need to be applied to 
do a full restore.<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><B>Selection of Backup Methods</B> - most administrators schedule an 

initial full backup followed by periodic (weekly or monthly) full or 
consolidation backups and frequent (daily) incremental or differential 
backups.</P>
<BR><BR>

<A NAME="8"><H3>Expiration Date</H3></A>

<P>Each time a backup job runs it creates an output called a "saveset."  The
purpose of a backup is to be able to recreate any file or file system that is
currently active on your hard drive if it is deleted or damaged.  Backups are
not intended for long term <A HREF="primer.html #8.1">archiving</A>, but 
rather are to help restore your hard drive in the event of data loss.  
Therefore, as part of any automated backup system, savesets are assigned 
expiration dates to minimize unneeded clutter.
For example, a full backup or consolidation backup saveset and all incremental
backup savesets might be scheduled to expire one week after the next full or
consolidation backup is scheduled to run.  If you are running monthly full or
consolidation backups, then the expiration date for each saveset should be at
least 38 days (31 + 7) from the date of the last full/consolidation backup.
</P><CENTER><P>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>
<A NAME="8.1"><H3>Archiving</H3></A>

<P>Archives are different than backups.  A backup allows you to restore your 
disk drive to its recent state in the event of a problem.  Archives are for 
long term preservation of data that may in fact be permanently deleted from 
the hard drive.  Unlike backups, archives have expiration dates measured in 
many months or years.  Some archives are even saved permanently.  SafetyPosit 
supports archiving as well as backup and provides powerful software tools for 
grooming file systems to identify candidates for archiving.
</P><CENTER><P>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>
<A NAME="6"><H3>Encryption</H3></A>

<P>The purpose of encryption is to make intercepted data transmissions or 
stolen tapes unintelligible without the decryption key.  Encryption is a 
process whereby data is transformed to appear patternless and meaningless to 
any viewer. Only the owner of the encryption/decryption "key" can restore the 
data to its original readable format.  SafetyPosit incorporates advanced 
encryption technology from RSA Data Security, Inc., a recognized leader 
in commercial data security software.  SafetyPosit uses RSA's RC2 encryption 
algorithm with a 128-bit private key.  Older algorithms, such as DES, don't 
offer the same degree of protection because their key size is considered too 
short for today's fast computers.</P>

<P>SafetyPosit encrypts all data, even directory information, before it is
transmitted.  This offers users two very important protections.  First, if
someone attempted to intercept the data you send us over the Internet, they
could not read it.  Even if an interceptor knew what file he wanted, he 
couldn't even determine if it were present in the data stream since directory 
information is also encrypted.  A 128-bit encryption key poses 2 to the 128 
power possible combinations (2^128) making it virtually impossible to crack 
the code even with the most advanced computers available.</P>  

<P>A second protection offered by this level of encryption is that no one with
access to our storage site can read your data.  This includes all SafetyPosit
operators and service technicians.  Thus, your key should be stored in a safe
place (either on paper, on removable magnetic media or both) since your data
cannot be restored without the key.  Access to the key should be limited the
responsible systems administration personnel.</P
<P><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>

<A NAME="6.1"><H3>Node Authentication</H3></A>

<P>Besides protecting the data itself with 
<A HREF="primer.html #6">encryption</A>, SafetyPosit prevents unauthorized 
usage with node authentication.  Node authentication is the process
by which SafetyPosit can confirm the true identity of any computer it
communicates with.  This makes it impossible to impersonate an authorized
SafetyPosit user.</P>

<P>SafetyPosit incorporates advanced node authentication technology from RSA 
Data Security, Inc., a recognized leader in commercial data security 
software.  Node authentication is based on RSA's public-key cryptosystem.  
Each node has both a public and private key.  To encrypt a message, the 
sender uses its own private key and the receiver's public key.  To decrypt, 
the receiver uses its own private key and the sender's public key.  Neither 
party knows the other's private key and each party knows the other's public 
key.  This method allows the sender and receiver to exchange decryption 
information without it being compromised.  SafetyPosit uses public-key 
cryptography to enable node authentication based on digital signatures.  
Public/private key cryptography is based on complex mathematical 
relationships regarding large prime numbers.  A <A HREF="primer.html #6.2">
technical explanation</A> is provided by RSA Data Security.</P>
<P><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>

<A NAME="6.2"><H3>Technical Explanation of How RSA's Public-key 
Cryptosystem Works</H3></A>

<P>RSA is a public-key cryptosystem for both encryption and authentication; 
it was invented in 1977 by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Leonard Adleman 
[RSA78].  It works as follows: take two large primes, p and q, and find their 
product n = pq; n is called the modulus.  Choose a number, e, less than n 
and relatively prime to (p-1)(q-1), which means that e and (p-1)(q-1) have no 
common factors except 1. Find another number d such that (ed - 1) is 
divisible by (p-1)(q-1). The values e and d are called the public and private 
exponents, respectively. The public key is the pair (n,e); the private key is 
(n,d). The factors p and q maybe kept with the private key, or destroyed.<P>

<P>It is difficult (presumably) to obtain the private key d from the public key
(n,e). If one could factor n into p and q, however, then one could obtain the
private key d. Thus the security of RSA is related to the assumption that
factoring is difficult. An easy factoring method or some other feasible attack
would "break" RSA.</P> 

<P>Here is how RSA can be used for privacy and authentication (in practice, the
actual use is slightly different.  Suppose Alice wants to send a message m to
Bob. Alice creates the ciphertext c by exponentiating: c = me mod n, where e 
and n are Bob's public key. She sends c to Bob. To decrypt, Bob also 
exponentiates: m = cd mod n; the relationship between e and d ensures that 
Bob correctly recovers m. Since only Bob knows d, only Bob can decrypt.</P

<P>RSA authentication: Suppose Alice wants to send a message m to Bob in such 
a way that Bob is assured that the message is authentic and is from Alice. 
Alice creates a digital signature s by exponentiating: s = md mod n, 
where d and n are Alice's private key. She sends m and s to Bob. To verify 
the signature, Bob exponentiates and checks that the message m is 
recovered: m = se mod n, where e and n are Alice's public key.</P>

<P>Thus encryption and authentication take place without any sharing of private
keys: each person uses only other people's public keys and his or her own
private key. Anyone can send an encrypted message or verify a signed message,
using only public keys, but only someone in possession of the correct private
key can decrypt or sign a message.</P
<P><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>

<A NAME="7"><H3>Compression</H3></A>

<P>Compression is used to extend the effective capacity of storage media.  
For example, an 8mm cartridge with a 20-GB capacity without compression can
typically hold 40-GB with compression.  The compression ratio (compressed vs.
non-compressed size) depends on the data itself.  The more repeated patterns in
the data, the better the compression will be, but ratios of 50% are common.</P>

<P>Compression can be done in one of two places, in software or hardware.  
Software compression is generally done at the source to reduce transmission 
time over a network and to reduce storage size.  Most modern tape drives 
perform compression in hardware but performing both software and hardware 
compression is of little benefit as the output of the software compression 
will be incompressible since it will not have very many repeating patterns.</P>

<P>Another reason to perform compression in software is if the data written to 
tape is also being encrypted.  If this is the case, the compression should be
performed before the encryption.  The reason being that encrypted data does not
compress very well, as the encrypted data does not have many repeating patterns
(it is the goal of an encryption algorithm to have no patterns at all).</P>
<P><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>

<A NAME="9"><H3>Internet Access to SafetyPosit</H3></A>

<P>SafetyPosit is designed to be accessible via the Internet.  This method of
communication has several advantages over other possible choices.  The number 
of users that have access to the Internet is rapidly expanding and is quite
diverse.  It includes everyone from home PC users to employees of the largest
corporations.  Even the formerly competing on-line services are now offering
ever improving access to the Internet.</P>
<P>
Aside from ubiquity, there are other characteristics of the Internet that make
it ideal for SafetyPosit.  Some of these include the fact that access to the
Internet is typically provided on a flat rate basis which is both usage and
distance independent.  This is important since SafetyPosit is likely to 
generate considerable incremental traffic from users in many different 
locations.  Also the Internet has a reduced usage from roughly 8PM EST to 
8AM EST.  This is ideal for SafetyPosit since it is best to schedule it to 
run when file activity is minimal and maximum network bandwidth is available.
</P><P>
With all the positive attributes, there is one Internet attribute that could
raise concern.  The Internet is a public network and any data that flows over
the Internet, passes by many doors.  Security is therefore a reasonable 
concern.</P>
<P>
To address this issue, SafetyPosit incorporates advanced <A HREF=
"primer.html #6">encryption</A> and <A HREF="primer.html #6.1">node
authentication</A> software from RSA Data Security, Inc.  SafetyPosit will 
not talk to any node unless it has been authenticated.  This prevents 
impostor nodes from accessing SafetyPosit.  SafetyPosit will not accept 
any backup data unless it has been encrypted.  This means that our 
SafetyPosit staff is incapable of reading your private data, as is anyone 
else your data passes enroute to SafetyPosit.</P>
<P>
There are several different ways to connect to the Internet.  These include
everything from dial modems to dedicated leased lines.  The following discusses
the performance and benefits of each.</P>  
<CENTER><P>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>
<BR><BR>

<P><A NAME="10"><B>Dial Modems</B></A> - dial modems are inexpensive and easy 
to configure and use over standard telephone lines for access to the 
Internet.  At a maximum speed of 28,800 bits per second (bps), it would take 
6 minutes to send a 1 Megabyte file (assumes 50% compression, 25% TCP/IP 
overhead, and 50% of nominal throughput).  This performance is adequate for 
many individual user applications where daily incremental backups may be less 
than 1MB and monthly consolidation backups may be less than 50 MB.  However, 
a modem link to the Internet is not likely to be sufficient for large server 
backups.<BR><BR><CENTER>  
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><A NAME="11"><B>ISDN</B></A> - ISDN stands for Integrated Services Digital 
Network and is a high speed dial up service that can carry both data a voice. 
The most common form of ISDN is called "Basic Rate" and is capable of carrying 
data access to the Internet at up to 128,000 bps.  At this speed, it would 
take about 13 minutes to perform a 10 MB incremental backup (assumes 50% 
compression, 25% TCP/IP overhead, and 50% of nominal throughput).  This makes 
ISDN outstanding for individual users and ideal for small server applications.
<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><A NAME="12"><B>Dedicated T1 access</B></A> - for larger organizations, it 
is becoming common to have a dedicated or leased line connection to the 
Internet.  This may be at "T1" speeds.  T1 operates at 1.544 Mbps or 54 times 
faster than modem.  At this speed, it would take about 11 minutes to perform 
a 100 MB backup or 108 minutes to perform a 1 GigaByte backup (assumes 50% 
compression, 25% TCP/IP overhead, and 50% of nominal throughput).  Dedicated 
access lines are not limited to T1 alone.  Most telephone carriers offer 
dedicated access lines starting at permanently attached modem lines and 
running all the way up to T3 lines at 45 Mbps.  Some Internet Service Providers
(ISPs) are allowing large users to attach at speeds up to T3.<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>

<P><A NAME="13"><B>Cable Modems</B></A> - there are an increasing number of 
new technologies that will be available in the next year or two that will 
dramatically increase the speed of Internet access without significantly 
increasing the cost.  These technologies include cable modems.  Cable modems 
are something that cable TV providers can offer so that data users can access 
unused channels on the cable system for two way data.  Internet access on a 
shared 10 Mbps channel is one of the promising applications for cable 
modems.  Because the 10 Mbps access is shared like ethernet, the sustained 
effective throughput is likely to be around 2 Mbps during low usage periods, 
and less during high usage periods.  With a cable modem, a 100 MB backup 
would take about 4 minutes (assumes 50% compression, 25% TCP/IP overhead,
and 20% of nominal throughput).<BR><BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>


<P><A NAME="14"><B>ADSL</B></A> - To compete with cable modems, some 
telephone carriers have been doing pilots with a technology called ADSL 
or asymmetric digital subscriber line.  This is a higher speed alternative 
to ISDN for Internet access.  ADSL would allow SafetyPosit users to send 
backups at speeds up to 640 Kbps and to restore at speeds up to 6 Mbps.<BR>  
<BR><CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P>


<P><A NAME="19"><B>Other</B></A> - Direct access via telephone carriers 
using Frame Relay and Private Line are also options which are technically feasible.  These options may or may not be more costly.  They should be examined on 
a case by case basis, and probably would be used by larger companies.<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<EM>[Use the 'Back' button on your browser to return to the previous page.]
</EM></CENTER></P> <BR><BR>



<BR><BR>
