<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Software Partner's THRUnet&#174</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><H1>THRUnet&#174, The UNIX to OpenVMS Backup and Restore System</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<H2>DESCRIPTION</H2>

<P>THRUnet is a backup and restore product for UNIX systems that enables UNIX 
workstations to be backed up to DEC VAX and Alpha storage devices. THRUnet 
offers OpenVMS operations personnel and UNIX users the security of knowing 
that valuable corporate data is being protected by standard site backup 
procedures. With THRUnet, UNIX users need no special knowledge of VMS 
commands to perform backup and restore procedures.
</P>
<HR>
<H2>FEATURES</H2>
<H3>Backup and Restore for UNIX systems</H3>
<P>THRUnet allows UNIX workstation users to back up and restore their files easily to any VAX or Alpha storage device.  Backups and restores are accomplished using standard UNIX commands, so that no special knowledge of OpenVMS is required.  UNIX users have the security of knowing that they can control file backup and restore, while data center personnel are satisfied that all corporate data is being protected. 

<H3>Centralized Backup Operations</H3>
<P>With THRUnet, backups of UNIX workstations to OpenVMS tape drives can be initiated from a central site. This centralization helps companies save money by eliminating the need for additional storage hardware on UNIX systems and by maximizing VAX and Alpha storage investments. </P>

<H3>Individual File and Full Disk Backup/Restore</H3>
<P>THRUnet allows UNIX users to back up and restore files individually, on demand. THRUnet  implements full operating system security throughout the process. This gives users security, control and responsibility for individual file backups and restores. By using THRUnet with <A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A>, The OpenVMS Media Management System, full disk backups can be managed by data center operations personnel to run automatically and to be integrated with site-specific backup procedures.</P>

<H3>Security</H3>
<P>THRUnet provides greater data security by eliminating local tape devices on workstations. Files can be protected from unauthorized removal by directing backups to a central VAX or AXP and storing all backup tapes in a central location. </P>

<H3>Standard UNIX formats</H3>
<P>UNIX users do not have to learn OpenVMS commands to back up their files to the OpenVMS system. THRUnet recognizes most UNIX backup command formats, including tar, cpio, and dump.</P>

<H3>Tape Labeling and Formats</H3>
<P>THRUnet gives UNIX systems the sophistication of OpenVMS by recognizing multi-file backups. Multiple archive files sent to an OpenVMS system for backup can be managed in OpenVMS fashion by using ANSI labels. ANSI standards allow multiple files containing OpenVMS backup savesets and/or UNIX archives to be placed on a single tape volume. Alternatively, a single archive file can span multiple tape volumes. THRUnet also allows OpenVMS tape drives to make non-ANSI UNIX compliant tapes. This sophistication ensures complete backup of files regardless of length or location on the backup reel and makes backup tapes readable by UNIX systems.</P>

<H3>History Files</H3>
<P>Using THRUnet, online history files are created by each backup and restore procedure when using tar or cpio. History logs can be accessed by workstation users for information on file location, reel ID, saveset, etc. History files can also be used by other applications to access archived or backed up files. In addition, information on file restores can be useful for auditing purposes.</P>

<H3>Resource Management</H3>
<P>THRUnet provides control over media resources by allowing different levels of user access. Operations personnel have the ability to restrict users to specific media devices for backup/restore procedures. This feature encourages efficient use of media hardware and centralization of backup operations.</P>

<H3>TAPESYS Interface</H3>
<P>THRUnet interfaces with <A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A>, The OpenVMS Media Management System, to provide complete management of the media library. All media used in backup procedures are cycled through media pools for efficient usage and to prevent unauthorized use. THRUnet verifies all tape labels through <A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A> so that data can never be lost by accidental overwrite. An online history database of all UNIX and OpenVMS backup files is maintained in the host OpenVMS system for fast, accurate location of files.</P>
<HR>

<H2>SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS</H2>
<P>OpenVMS 6.0+
<P>VAX-VMS V5.4+
<P>TCP/IP from one of the following:
<UL>
<LI>TCPware for VMS from Process Software Corporations
<LI>MultiNet from TGV</LI>
<LI>PathWay from Wollongong</LI>
<LI>DEC TCP/IP Services for VMS</LI>
</UL></P>
<HR>
<H2>SYSTEM SUGGESTIONS</H2>
<P><A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A> for media management</P>
<HR>
<H2>CURRENTLY SUPPORTED CLIENTS</H2>
<UL>
<LI>DEC ULTRIX-RISC V4.2A+</LI>
<LI>DEC ULTRIX-VAX V4.2+</LI>
<LI>Digital UNIX</LI>
<LI>SunOS (Sun4. architecture)</LI>
<LI>Solaris</LI>
<LI>HP-UX (HP9000, HP9000, HP-UX A.08.07 and A.09.01+)</LI>
<LI>IBM RS/6000</LI>
<LI>SGI-Silicon Graphics IRIX</LI>
<LI>Intergraph</LI>
<LI>SCO.</LI>
</UL>
<P>Call Software Partners for information on additional client support.</P>
<HR><CENTER>
