<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Software Partner's THRUway&#174</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><H1>THRUway&#174, The OpenVMS Remote Device Access System</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
<H2>DESCRIPTION</H2>

<P>THRUway, The OpenVMS Remote Device Access System, bridges the gap from a 
remote VAX or Alpha AXP to a central VAX or Alpha, simplifies file access, and provides easy and safe management of remote data from the main site.  THRUway</P>
<UL>
<LI>transfers data in the context of any standard VMS I/O format including BACKUP,</LI>
<LI>makes a clustered tape drive appear as a local drive to remote users,</LI>
<LI>makes a remote disk drive appear as a local drive,</LI>
<LI>allows backup of files from a CPU without a tape drive to a tape drive on a central CPU,</LI>
<LI>provides centralized backup of remote CPU's,</LI>
<LI>works in conjunction with <A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS&#174</A> to schedule and drive backups of remote disks,</LI>
<LI>eliminates the need for operator involvement at the remote site,</LI>
<LI>prints local files on a remote OpenVMS printer,</LI>
<LI>runs images resident on a remote system,</LI>
<LI>uses both DCL and menu interfaces, and</LI>
<LI>installs layered software locally using VMSINSTAL and a remote tape drive.</LI>
</UL>
<HR>
<H2>FEATURES and BENEFITS</H2>
<UL>
<LI><H3>Remote Device Access</H3>
<P>THRUway provides access to remote disk drives, tape drives, and printers. This allows you to spread the processing workload over your network, providing cluster-like capabilities without the cluster expense. Access to all three device types gives you the greatest value for your software dollars.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Runs on OpenVMS Systems</H3>
<P>THRUway can be used on any CPU running the OpenVMS operating system.</P>
</LI>

<LI><H3>Employs Standard VMS I/O Format</H3>
<P>THRUway enables data from remote VAX/Alpha AXP nodes to be transferred to and from a tape drive on a main system in the context of any standard VMS I/O format, including BACKUP.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Easy-to-Use Interface</H3>
<P>THRUway creates a logical name on the local node that has the look and feel of a disk or tape drive on the remote node by establishing a DECnet link between the two nodes. I/O requests on the local nodes are made to the new logical entity. The requests are passed over DECnet to the remote node for processing and any data and status information is returned back to the local node.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Eliminates Lost Files</H3>
<P>THRUway allows remote users access to the tape and disk drives at the central site. Backups of remote disks can be run easily, and the possibility of lost files is greatly reduced.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Quick File Access</H3>
<P>THRUway eliminates the need to go in and out of DECnet to perform multiple file accesses on a remote node.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Runs Remote Images</H3>
<P>THRUway allows you to run most images that are on another CPU's disk. With THRUway, you need only one copy of that image.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Network Monitoring</H3>
<P>The THRUWAY MONITOR command, which monitors an active THRUway link, provides detailed statistics of network performance. This feature gives system managers a blueprint for adjusting THRUway tuning logicals to enhance performance.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Generic Device Names</H3>
<P>With THRUway, all tape devices in the network can be table-defined, enabling generic access to available drives on any remote server. The requesting user need not know the specific device names of the tape drives configured on the server node. Instead, the user can simply request a type of drive, such as TA90, or one capable of 6250-bpi.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Use VMSINSTAL Over DECnet</H3>
<P>You don't need a tape drive on your local node to install layered software. Just use THRUway to access a drive on a remote VAX/AXP.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Remote Printing</H3>
<P>THRUway lets you take advantage of printers on other CPUs in your network. Now you don't have to copy your file over the network before printing. THRUway lets you work as though you had all the printer power on your own CPU.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Efficient Backups</H3>
<P>No longer do you have to make a local saveset via VMS BACKUP and then COPY the saveset across to a waiting tape. THRUway allows you to back up remote devices directly, quickly, and unattended.</P></LI> 

<LI><H3><A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A> Interface</H3>
<P>THRUway works in conjunction with <A HREF="tapesys.html">TAPESYS</A>, The OpenVMS Tape Management System, to schedule and run complete backups of remote disks from a central site. To effect a remote backup, the operator simply hangs a specified tape on the local tape drive when directed by the system.</P></LI>

<LI><H3><A HREF="hierarchy.html">HIERARCHY&#174</A> Interface</H3>
<P>THRUway works with <A HREF="hierarchy.html">HIERARCHY</A>, The OpenVMS Hierarchical Storage Manager, to archive and restore files to and from remote devices. These products provide an efficient hierarchical approach to file storage.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Warranty/Support</H3>
<P>Software Partners provides 24-hour support, 365 days per year. THRUway carries a complete warranty and support for ninety days. Maintenance is then renewable annually.</P></LI>

<LI><H3>Product training, including telephone training is available.</H3></LI>
</UL>
<HR>
<H2>How Are We Different?</H2>
<UL>
<LI>THRUway accesses remote tapes, disks, and printers. You can run backups on one CPU for all your remote VAXes/AXPs, or in any combination you wish.</LI>

<LI>THRUway works with TCP/IP and DECnet networks.</LI>

<LI>THRUway has a menu interface for easy use, or a simple DCL interface.</LI>

<LI>THRUway allows channel tuning and reporting for optimal data transfer.</LI>
</UL>
<HR><CENTER>
<I>
