<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Software Partner's TT/Recon</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<CENTER><H1>TT/RECON, The VAX/VMS Terminal Reconnaissance Tool</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
<H2>DESCRIPTION</H2>
<P>TT/RECON, The VAX/VMS Terminal Reconnaissance Tool, is a software product that allows a user to monitor another user's terminal. Monitoring can be interactive, so that System Managers and help desk support personnel can train or assist end users conveniently from their own desks.</P>
<P>TT/RECON offers flexibility in terminal monitoring. System Managers have the ability to customize the monitoring process to optimize training and maintain security. </P>
<P>With TT/RECON you are able to:
<UL>
<LI>monitor target terminals, usernames, or PIDs interactively or in batch,</LI>
<LI>list out a user's entire DCL recall buffer (well beyond the standard 20 commands presented by VMS),</LI>
<LI>start monitoring a terminal upon login,</LI>
<LI>capture monitored output in a log file,</LI>
<LI>secretly watch a terminal,</LI>
<LI>reject monitoring of terminals (available to privileged users only),</LI>
<LI>detect monitoring of your own terminal,</LI>
<LI>suspend a monitored terminal's process,</LI>
<LI>log all uses of TT/RECON,</LI>
<LI>monitor RT terminals from remote VMS nodes,</LI>
<LI>restrict users who are able to be monitored,</LI>
<LI>set a password for access to TT/RECON,</LI>
<LI>monitor your own terminal to save the session.</LI>
</UL>
<HR>
<H2>FEATURES</H2>
<H3>Network Compatibility</H3>
<P>Users can monitor any interactive process over the network, including remote terminals from other VMS nodes. Network support is enabled during installation. When a user tries to monitor another user on a remote terminal, TT/RECON will establish a network connection and actually monitor the user at his host terminal. </P>
<H3>RT Terminal Monitoring</H3>
<P>When a user specifies a remote terminal or a process which has an RT terminal, 
TT/RECON traces back the chain of processes between the remote terminal and 
the initial terminal name (from which a SET HOST command was first issued). 
Then it establishes a network connection and monitors the host terminal. The command, TTRECON SHOWRT, outputs information about RT terminal traceback.</P>
<H3>Restricted Monitoring</H3>
<P>System Managers can restrict monitoring to a specific set of users with the ENABLE feature. Users who are to be monitored are set up with a specific logical in their job 
table that allows monitoring.</P>
<H3>User Interface</H3>
<P>The user accesses TT/RECON by use of simple DCL commands. The TTRECON 
MONITOR command is the driving force behind the application, and it has many qualifiers which control how monitoring takes place. Other commands include TTRECON PASSWORD, HELP, STOP, and SHOWRT.</P>
<H3>Help Desk Support</H3>
<P>TT/RECON allows you to list the user's DCL recall buffer so you can see what the user typed before you started monitoring. Unlike VMS, which presents only the last 
20 commands for your own terminal, TT/RECON gives you access to the entire users' recall buffer, which could be upwards of 100 DCL commands.  Using TT/RECON, 
you can monitor a terminal and see what the user is typing. When you begin monitoring, the user receives a message that he/she is being monitored (unless you are monitoring 
secretly). Typing commands on your keyboard allows you to fix the user's mistakes because TT/RECON's active monitoring feature allows you to participate in the user's terminal session. </P>
<H3>Security</H3>
<P>TT/RECON allows monitoring of terminals secretly. If you suspect a security breach, you can monitor a terminal based on PID, terminal device name, or username. The target terminal can be prevented from receiving a message that it's being monitored.</P>
<P>Privileged users can prevent their terminals from being monitored, as well as determine if someone is monitoring them.</P>
<P>System Managers can use the "kill" feature of TT/RECON to instantly suspend a target terminal's process if it is jeopardizing the system's integrity. </P> 
<P>TT/RECON can be set up to start monitoring when a particular user logs on, or a particular terminal is logged onto. Monitoring can be directed to your screen or to a log file which you can print out later for study. You can also log off any current user who has forgotten to do so before leaving for the day.</P>
<H3>Password Protection</H3>
<P>System Managers can restrict the group of users accessing TT/RECON by setting up a password to the TT/RECON image. Users must know the current password to engage TT/RECON. This prevents unauthorized users from monitoring other terminals.</P>
<HR>
<H2>Warranty/Support</H2>
<P>Software Partners provides 24-hour support, 365 days per year. TT/RECON clients are provided with total warranty and support for ninety days. Maintenance is then renewable annually. </P>
<P>Product training, including telephone training is available.</P>
<HR><CENTER>
