<HEAD>
 <TITLE>Main Window</TITLE>
<H1><CENTER>The StorageCenter Main Window</CENTER></H1>
<A><CENTER><IMG SRC="Line.Gif"></CENTER></A>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=450>
<P>
The StorageCenter main window is the access point to all windows and dialog boxes available on the Graphical User Interface (GUI).  The main window displays selectable icons and menus representing StorageCenter environments and functions.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<BR>
<H3><CENTER>StorageCenter Environments</CENTER></H3>

<A><IMG SRC="SC_GUI.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=4 HEIGHT=350 WIDTH=200></A>

The <A HREF="administration.html">Administration</A> environment allows you to define the essential information StorageCenter needs to perform all functions.  In this environment you add hosts, devices, volumes, locations, media, volume cycles and pools, and users and groups to the database.  StorageCenter uses this database information for writing, retrieving, and storing your data.

<P>
The <A HREF="mediamanagement.html">Media Management</A> environment can track and control the allocation, usage, location, expiration, and cycling of all media volumes and savesets.  Media Management can help prevent against accidental overwrites and generate reports on media status.

<P>
The <A HREF="backup.html">Backup</A> environment allows you to set up all information needed to perform a StorageCenter backup.  With Backup you can conveniently select file systems, backup devices and job schedules, and view important information about scheduled backups.

<P>
The  <A HREF="restore.html">Restore</A> environment allows you to restore Backup files, directories, and complete file systems.  Restore makes it easy to locate the data you want and restore it back to disk.

<P>
The <A HREF="archiving.html">Archiving</A> environment allows you to control methods for migrating files from limited disk space to virtually limitless off-line media.  You can use Archiving to clean up your file system or free valuable disk storage space.
<P>

<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD>
<P>
</TD>

<HR>
<TD WIDTH=450>
<P>
In addition to the environments described above, StorageCenter provides four tools you can access from the main window:
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<OL>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballblue.gif"</A>
Volume Initializer - quickly initializes a new volume or range of volumes.
</OL>

<OL>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballblue.gif"</A>
<A HREF="jobcalendar.html">Job Calendar</A> - presents all scheduled jobs by date.
</OL>

<OL>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballblue.gif"</A>
Backup File Browser - quickly locates files or directories that have been backed up.
</OL>

<OL>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballblue.gif"</A>
Log File Viewer - views audit trails of completed jobs.
</OL>

<BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=450>
<P> 
Prior to setting up backups, restores, media management or archives you must perform a few Administration functions.  Next, you will view some of the Administration information you will need to set up at the start of using StorageCenter. 

<P>
We suggest that new StorageCenter users work sequentially through this demo.  Click on the Forward button at the bottom of this page to continue the StorageCenter demo.  If you are already familar with StorageCenter, you can click on any of the underlined words above to move directly to information about that environment or feature.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

