<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Internet Backup</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.voiceisp.net/backgrounds/marble4.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<H2><CENTER>SafetyPosit Whitepaper</CENTER>
</H2>
<H2><CENTER>Outsourcing Backups Over The Internet</CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gifs/SafetyPosit_Main.gif">
</CENTER>
<BR>
<H3><CENTER>Ask Yourself These Questions</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>W</FONT>hen is the last time you backed up your desktop?  When 
is the last time your server was backed up?  Recently?  Great.  Where are the
floppies?  Where are the tapes? Hopefully at the vault.  They are?  Great.
How long would it take to restore a critical file?  And if you were to call
the vault and request a return of a 'file' what would the vault send back?
Just the one file?  Or would they send back a whole tape, or even a BOX of tapes?  And if they did, what would be left at the vault for protection?
<BR><BR>
Please read on!
<BR>
<H3><CENTER>What Is SafetyPosit?</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>S</FONT>afetyPosit is a service to provide secure backup of data 
across a network.  The network can be the public Internet, leased lines or 
dialup phone lines.  The software that enables the service will reside on the 
customer's computers and on the Company's storage computers in the Company's 
secure storage room.  The software will provide a means to schedule recurring 
backups of data across the network to the Company's storage hardware.  
SafetyPosit will provide nearly all capabilities found in StorageCenter, the 
Company's flagship software product.  Exceptions include the vaulting of 
volumes and some administrative features.  
A <A HREF="/SafetyPosit/Whitepaper_slides/sld01.html">quick review</A> of 
several slides will provide a better understanding of how SafetyPosit works.<BR>
<H3><CENTER>What's Happening Without SafetyPosit?</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>M</FONT>ost small organizations (those with fewer than 
thirty computer workstations)
do not maintain regular backup schedules.  They do not assign the task to
one person, but instead leave individuals with the responsibility to backup
their own systems.  Consequently, in most small organizations, backups just
are not done.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT> typical medium-sized organization (thirty to two 
hundred workstations)
may run backups regularly, but may suffer from using multiple backup programs
gathered over time, and perhaps used since it was a small organization.
 Most backup products are not scalable.  Furthermore, when a medium-sized
company does run backups, they often find they do not have enough tapes
to warrant a professional offsite storage service.  Consequently offsite
storage is not done, and the company is vulnerable to onsite disasters.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>M</FONT>ost large data processing operations have had 
backup programs operating
for years.  The people at these large sites manage great numbers of tapes,
and have employed regular backup products to track files, savesets and tapes.
 Typical large sites may be creating twenty to one hundred billion characters
(20-100 gigabytes(GB)) of backup data per day, and writing this to tapes.
 These tapes are stored on shelves in the site's tape library, where they
remain for a prescribed time period.  A common schedule might call for 
incremental backup tapes to be made each night and stored for a week.  
Full backups are made once each week and stored for a month, with the 
exception of the last full backup made each month being kept for a year.  
In some industries,
regulatory agencies may require that backups of certain data be kept for
seven years, or thirteen years, or forever.  Managing any number of tape
cartridges greater than one hundred generally requires some kind of automated
software.  [This is the nature of StorageCenter, the Company's primary software
product.]<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT>s part of their daily or weekly operation, larger, 
more sophisticated sites
usually send certain tapes offsite for storage.  Offsite storage provides
a means of recoverability in the event the data processing center, or the
disk drives, or the computer itself, is damaged.  Several successful companies
exist to provide offsite storage services, including Iron Mountain, Arcus,
The Fortress and many regional and independent organizations.<BR>
<H3><CENTER>How Tapes Get To The Vault</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he typical scenario has an operator reading tape 
numbers from a system-generated
list and pulling the respective tapes from racks.  The tapes are placed
in storage containers, and the containers are picked up by a vault service
company.  They're loaded into a van.  Humorously, it is usually a chevy
truck, thus giving rise to the acronym CTAM, for Chevy Truck Access
Method.  CTAM is what we are eradicating with SafetyPosit!  The driver 
may make multiple pickups
at other sites before returning to the vault location.  The containers are
transferred into the vault and placed on shelves.  Most large, sophisticated
vault supply companies track tapes and containers using barcodes and scanners,
so they can quickly determine where any tape is in the warehouse.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>W</FONT>hen a customer needs to restore a file, it is up to 
the customer's onsite
media management system to relate the name of the needed file to the tape
it is on, and the container the tape is in, at the vault.  The customer
makes the determination and places a call to the vault service provider
to request the return of the appropriate container.  The tape is located,
taken out of the container, placed on a truck and returned to the customer.
 If the tape was originally placed in a container that was locked by the
customer, the whole container is returned, with all the other tapes in it
as well.<BR>
<H3><CENTER>Problems Using Conventional Backup and Storage</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>here are many unacceptable failure points in this 
common scenario, with each failure in one or more of three categories:  
failure to act, human error or uncontrollable or extenuating circumstances.  
There are also significant expenses that, with the advent of the SafetyPosit 
concept, will become unnecessary.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B><I>Failure to Act</I></B></CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE=5>C</FONT>learly obvious in the smaller sites is the failure 
to properly implement
backup procedures.  It can be easily demonstrated that, on a character for
character basis, information is far more valuable to a small company than
it is to a large company.  A small company that fails to properly manage
its backups is threatening its own growth.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B><I>Human Error</I></B></CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE=5>F</FONT>irst among the human error possibilities, of course, 
is the opportunity
for the operator to <EM>mount the wrong tape</EM>.  To prevent this, the
customer's media management system verifies the proper tape by examining
the label. Some systems, though, allow the operator to override the rejection
warnings and proceed with the wrong tape.  This would be logged, however,
and it is expected that any operator who overrides has a valid reason for
doing so.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>N</FONT>ext is the possibility for the <EM>wrong tape to be 
placed in the vault-bound
container</EM>.  Though the operator works from a printed list, it is easy
to see that a simple transposition of characters on the list can result
from the wrong tape being pulled from a rack.  For example, if the list
shows tapes AB8442, YE8491 and QY6379, the operator might accidentally pull
tapes AB8442, YE8941 and QY6379.  This could lead to all kinds of data loss,
especially in the event of a disaster for which the offsite storage system
was designed to protect from in the first place.<BR>
<BR>
<EM><FONT SIZE=5>C</FONT>ontainers</EM>, which do not have customer names on 
the outside for
security reasons, <EM>can be mistakenly switched between customers</EM>.
 The container provided by the vault supplier looks like all other containers
carried by the delivery person, and in the back of a truck on a busy city
street, under the pressure of making time-sensitive deliveries and pickups,
they may all look alike.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT> <EM>tape within a container may be damaged</EM> while 
enroute to or from
the vault.  A traffic accident or a fall from a carriage onto a concrete
sidewalk can jolt a container enough to jar a tape cartridge inside, resulting
in damaged tape edges and partially or completely unreadable media.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>W</FONT>hen the customer needs to restore a file, he must 
retrieve the tape from the vault.  Since the tape is usually in a container 
locked by the customer, the entire container must be returned.  This 
<EM>endangers the other tapes in the container</EM>.  If the tape is not 
in a container, the single tape itself is retrieved, and at least the other 
files on the same tape are endangered.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>O</FONT>nce the customer has determined that a 
critical file has been deleted,
he places a call to the vault to retrieve the tape.  <EM>Precious time is
lost</EM> while the tape is located, picked, placed in a container, packed
in a van, and driven back to the customer site.  This is a costly transaction
as well, since the vault service charges for emergency deliveries.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B><I>Uncontrollable or Extenuating Circumstances</I></B></CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE=5>N</FONT>atural disasters occur every day.  Buildings burn, 
floods rage, and
storms blow.  Beyond acts of nature, corporate America must prepare to deal
with the growing threat of sabotage and terrorism.  Directly applied terrorism,
against a particular company, is more predictable than randomly applied
terrorism, done against a population at large.  Either way, data and services
are lost.  Among the standard precautions to preserve life and physical
property (evacuation plans, site security, first aid training, advanced
planning, etc.) is the need for data security through proper backup.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B><I>Unnecessary Expenses</I></B></CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE=5>O</FONT>perations staff salaries and related costs 
are not going down. While
the price of tape libraries continues to drop slightly every other year,
the cost to manage them is rising.  Financing costs, power costs, service
expenses and floor expenses are not coming down.<BR>
<H3><CENTER>The SafetyPosit Response</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he problems cited here are almost unanimously 
related to human failure.
 If not human failure, then to lost time and great inconvenience.  SafetyPosit
addresses each of these problems:<BR>
<BR>
<P><CENTER><I><FONT SIZE=4>C</FONT>onventional Problem</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>he SafetyPosit Response<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>O</FONT>perator mounts wrong tape</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>ith SafetyPosit, no operator is ever involved, since 
only a robot mounts
tapes for storage and retrieval.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>rong tapes placed in containers</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>apes are not placed in containers, since data is 
backed up without tape,
directly and electronically to the remote storage site.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>ape goes to a competitor's site</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>N</FONT>o tapes are transferred.  To prevent the
downloading of a file to the wrong site, SafetyPosit employs RSA's 128-bit
Public Key Cryptosystem, using Digital Signatures to ensure accurate
point-to-point linking and transmission.<BR>

<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>ape is readable at the vault site</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>S</FONT>afetyPosit contains the RSA 128-bit Public
Key Cryptosystem, which enables immediate encryption of backed up data, before
the saveset leaves the desktop. The encrypted saveset is transmitted over the
network to the storage site, where it remains fully encrypted, unreadable by
anyone at the storage server site.  No one can ever read the file without the
key, which is solely in the possession of the customer.
<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>C</FONT>ontainers mistakenly switched</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>P</FONT>hysical containers are not an issue, since they're 
not used for moving files offsite.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>apes are subject to damage</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>F</FONT>iles are not written to tape for transfer; instead 
they're moved electronically to offsite magnetic storage.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>O</FONT>ther tapes endangered</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>hen a file is identified for retrieving, it and only 
it is restored.  No other files are retrieved.  Furthermore, the original 
offsite copy remains offsite, in case it is needed again.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>P</FONT>recious time is lost</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>ime required is related to the speed of the 
communication link.  In T1 settings, file retrieval can be achieved in as 
little as two minutes, anywhere in the country.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>N</FONT>atural disasters</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>D</FONT>ata is safely stored at an offsite location, and can 
be restored to a hotsite facility or an alternative corporate operation 
with no additional effort.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>errorist threats</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>D</FONT>ata is encrypted and cannot be read by anyone but 
the person with the original key.<BR>
<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>U</FONT>nnecessary costs are rising</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>S</FONT>afetyPosit removes the need for operators hanging tapes, 
and eliminates the need for tape libraries, tape racks and related 
maintenance costs.</CENTER>
<P>
<H3><CENTER>The SafetyPosit Service</CENTER>
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he customer will use SafetyPosit to either supplement 
or replace his current backup operations, or as a new service to provide 
backup protection where none has been before.  In some large sites it is 
conceivable that SafetyPosit can replace all the backup operations.  This 
can be achieved using high-speed
dedicated communication links, such as fiber or T3.  But in most large sites,
it is expected that SafetyPosit will at least provide supplemental backup
services for moving strategic files offsite to safer storage.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>I</FONT>n many medium-sized sites, SafetyPosit can provide 
complete backup services in place of existing operations.  Sites backing up 
between five and 20 gigabytes of data per week can easily take advantage of 
SafetyPosit's scheduling mechanism, and coordinate an appropriate mix of 
incremental and full backups over the course of a week or a month.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>I</FONT>n small operations, (SOHO sites) SafetyPosit can be 
the basis for introducing sound backup practices where no backups are being 
done at all.  Computer users who are reluctant to purchase their own tape 
drives and tapes, or who have purchased them but haven't taken the time to 
run backups, will avail themselves of the opportunity to have their backups 
done automatically, overnight, without any effort on their part.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he system will eventually be configurable to remind 
the small system user that it is 'time to run the backup', depending on how 
many files the system has determined have changed since the last time a 
backup was run.  For instance, at the time the small user signals to leave 
his Internet provider's home page, he'd be asked if he wants to run a backup 
now, given the warning that certain files are new or have been changed since 
the last backup.
<BR>
<!--<H3><CENTER>Marketing Tools &amp; Methods</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he Company will employ its conventional tools, including 
