<H3><CENTER>Glossary of Terms</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR>
<DL>
<DT><B>Backup</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>o make a copy of a file in another place.  
The original file is left in
its original location.  People who need to read from or write to that file
in the future will use the original file in its original location. The copy
of the file, in another place, is kept in case the original file is lost
or corrupted. Compare 'backup' with 'move' which means to moves the only
copy of a file to another place, resulting in still one file, but in a new
location.  In a paper world, a backup is analogous to photocopying a paper
on your desk.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Full or Image Backup</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>M</FONT>ake copies of all files to another place, 
whether or not they have changed since they were last copied.  A full 
backup is useful for establishing a point in time when regard for various 
previous collections of incremental backups can be eliminated. A full backup 
is analogous to photocopying everything on your desk, regardless of whether a 
page has been there for a day, or a week or a month or since the desk was 
moved in.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Gigabyte</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT>bbreviated GB or gb.  
One billion (1,000,000,000) bytes, or characters
(a character being a letter, number or symbol - the word 'software' being
comprised of eight (8) characters or bytes.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Incremental Backup</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>M</FONT>ake a copy of a file to another 
place only if it has been changed since
the last time it was copied to that place.  If a file has been modified
(not simply read) since it was last copied, the copy is considered aged,
or in some cases obsolete, and a fresh copy of the modified file must be
made.  An incremental backup is analogous to making photocopies of papers
on your desk that have never been copied before, or which have been marked
up or otherwise written on since the last time you made copies.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Saveset</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT> collection of copies of one or more 
files that have been backed up.  During
a backup, individual files that are backed up are copied into one larger
saveset, or container file.  It is very much like a file folder which holds
one or more individual pieces of paper.  The individual pieces of paper
go together wherever the file folder goes.  If you hand someone the file
folder, you've handed that person all the papers in the folder at once.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Scalable</B>	<BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he characteristic of being able to 
move from one level to another.  A software
product is scalable if it works equally well for all sizes of demand put
upon it. For example, a small company employing nine people buys a payroll
system that has, in its database, enough space to allow two characters for
employee number.  The payroll system works well while the company grows
to sixty people.  Once the company needs to store more than one hundred
names in the system (allowing for attrition, it may have employed more than
one hundred people over time), the system fails to work.  It is not scalable.
 The company must find a payroll system designed to hold more than one hundred
names.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>SOHO</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he Small Office/Home Office marketplace.  
Corporate America's rampant schedule
of downsizing over the past ten years has given rise to a significant new
marketplace made up of entrepreneurial service providers operating out of
their homes or sharing office space.  These people have desktop computers
that generally go for long periods of time without being backed up.  If
they ever are backed up, they're backed up sporadically, and usually little
attention is given to managing a thorough sequencing of backup media.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>StorageCenter</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he Company's flagship storage management 
software system.  StorageCenter
(SC) is a licensed product sold over the telephone to MIS managers.  The
customer receives a CD and a copy of the product documentation in return
for a license fee.  The customer installs the software by herself, perhaps
with the assistance of our telephone support staff. 
The software, when installed
successfully, manages the customer's collection of tape cartridges, and
provides a complete means of defining, scheduling, running and reporting
on all regular backups at the customer site.  To use SC by itself, it is
incumbent upon the customer to have her own storage hardware, and her own
collection of tape cartridges.  SC by itself directs the customer as to
which cartridges should be used at any time, and which cartridges should
go to or come from any number of offsite storage vaults.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Storage Hardware</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>C</FONT>omputer disk drives, tape drives 
and automatic tape loaders (see 'Tape
Library') assembled to efficiently store data.  Disk drives are relatively
fast and relatively expensive, compared to tape.  Manufacturers of storage
hardware include Overland Data, Inc., StorageTek, Odetics and Exabyte.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Tape Library</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT> single hardware unit containing one or 
more tape drives, shelves with
slots to hold tape cartridges, and a robotic device to move the tapes from
the slots to the drives and back.  The more efficient units require that
the tapes display a barcode on the cover.  A barcode reader, mounted on
the robotic device (the arm) can read the code to determine which tape it
should retrieve.  A tape library is often referred to as a jukebox, for
its analogy to record players found in diners, which fetch the desired record
from a slot on a shelf and move it to the turntable, on demand.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<DT><B>Vault</B><BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT>n offsite storage location where 
tape cartridges are placed on shelves.
 A professionally managed vault has a constant temperature and humidity,
is clean, and secure.  The vault supplier usually manages tape locations
in a vault with the help of proprietary computer software, relating a tape's
unique identification number to its location in the vault, its owner, the
date it arrived and the date it is to return to the owner's facility.<BR>
<BR>
</DL>
<HR><CENTER>

<BR>


