<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Volume</TITLE>
<H1><CENTER>
<A><IMG SRC="administration.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE HSPACE=4 HEIGHT=75 WIDTH=75></A>
StorageCenter Administration</CENTER></H1>
<A><CENTER><IMG SRC="Line.Gif"></CENTER></A>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BR>
<H2><CENTER>Volume</CENTER></H2>

A volume is one of the essential Administration items you need to add to the StorageCenter database prior to setting up your backups and archives.  In StorageCenter, a volume is a physical medium (tape, CD-ROM, etc.) used to store data.  When peforming backups and archives, StorageCenter writes your data to a volume. You can view a list of the volumes defined in the database on the Volume window.

<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><A><IMG SRC="volumewin.gif" HSPACE=4 HEIGHT=350 WIDTH=575></A>
</CENTER>

<P>
Some powerful features of Volume Administration are volume ranges, ANSI labels, volume cycles and pools.  

<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20 ALIGN=TOP>
<A><IMG SRC="ballyellow.gif"
</A>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=400>
StorageCenter allows you to add single volumes or easily add ranges of volumes to the database.
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN=TOP>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballyellow.gif"
</A>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=400>
Each volume is automatically assigned an ANSI Label to help maintain control of the volumes and prevent valuable information from being overwritten.
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN=TOP>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballyellow.gif"
</A>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=400>
Volume cycles help keep track of where your volumes are located as they move offsite and to different locations.
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH=10 ALIGN=TOP>
<A><IMG SRC=" ballyellow.gif"
</A>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=400>
Volume pools group collections of volumes together in order for you to grant users read or write access to those volumes.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
Next, you will view information about defining devices (tape drives) in the database.

<BR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="device.html">Continue the StorageCenter demo<IMG SRC="arrow.gif" ALIGN=MIDDLE HSPACE=4></A>
</CENTER>

<br>
