<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What Is Electronic Vaulting?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<H2>What is electronic vaulting?</H2>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>E</FONT>lectronic vaulting is a new way of performing data 
backup and archiving. Electronic vaulting allows you to backup or archive 
your irreplaceable data to a secure, remote, professionally managed storage 
vault using electronic communications methods including the Internet, frame 
relay, dedicated lines, ISDN, or direct-dial telephone.  Electronic vaulting 
includes backup software to run on your system and a storage vault to receive 
your backups.  You provide the a connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>E</FONT>lectronic vaulting differs from traditional backup 
methods in several ways. First, instead of using single purpose hardware like 
a tape drive, electronic vaulting <A HREF="hardware.html">requires no special 
hardware</A>.  Instead, it can take advantage of the Internet access you may 
already have in place.  Second, electronic vaulting reduces the 
administrative burden by eliminating or reducing tape handling, cataloging, 
and storage.  Third, electronic vaulting reduces security risk since all 
off-site backups must be <A HREF="primer.html #6">encrypted</A> prior to 
transmission.  Finally, files may be restored immediately from an electronic 
vault.  No need to locate tapes and wait for them to be recalled and loaded.
</P>
<CENTER>
<BR><BR>
