<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How Does SafetyPosit(sm) Work?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#E6E8FA" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<H2>How does SafetyPosit(sm) work?</H2>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he first step to using SafetyPosit is to install our 
advanced backup software on the platforms that will be backed up.  This 
software is provided as part of the SafetyPosit service at no additional 
charge and may be downloaded from our Web site at the time of registration.  
Our SafetyPosit backup software draws on the technology of <A HREF=
"/StorageCenter.html">StorageCenter</A>, our complete storage management 
suite for distributed computing.
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he second step is to create a backup strategy for daily 
<A HREF="primer.html #3">incremental backups</A> and weekly or monthly <A HREF=
"primer.html #5">consolidation backups</A>.  You define a strategy by 
creating backup work orders.  A backup work order defines which disks, 
directories, and files will be backed up.
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he third step is to schedule the backup to run 
automatically.  Incremental backups are typically scheduled to run five or 
six days a week, usually outside of normal business hours.  Consolidation 
backups typically run weekly or monthly, on the weekend.  But your schedule 
is completely up to you.  If you want to maintain an offsite copy of your 
data that rarely changes, such as operating systems and software 
applications, you can also perform an initial baseline full backup.</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT>he fourth step is to test SafetyPosit by performing test 
backups and restores. This is the most important step since it will validate 
that SafetyPosit is working the way you want it.</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>O</FONT>nce SafetyPosit is up and running, everything else 
occurs automatically. SafetyPosit will start backup jobs on schedule.  For 
example, an incremental backup may kick off at 10 PM every week night.  The 
job starts by checking all target files to see if they have been modified 
since the last backup.  If they have been modified, they will be included in 
the backup job.  Next, SafetyPosit <A HREF="primer.html #7">compresses</A> 
and <A HREF="primer.html #6">encrypts</A> the files to be transmitted.  
Compression reduces the size of the file for faster transmission and 
encryption ensures that the files cannot be read by unauthorized parties.  
Finally, SafetyPosit begins transmitting the backup job using TCP/IP 
communications.  TCP/IP is the standard protocol specified for use on the 
Internet and can be used over private networks and dial up links as well.</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Y</FONT>our backup job is now on its way to our SafetyPosit 
storage vault over the Internet (or other communications link).  As a 
registered SafetyPosit user, our firewall allows your data to pass into our 
system.  Upon receipt, you data is placed on our RAID (redundant array of 
independent disks) server so that we immediately have redundant copies of 
your data.  Within 24 hours of receipt, your data will be copied to a high 
speed tape library where it will remain available until its <A HREF=
"primer.html #8">expiration date</A>.  All copies of your data remain 
encrypted so there is no chance of your security being compromised.</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT>fter a backup job completes, SafetyPosit updates your 
backup catalog so you can quickly locate any file you wish to restore.
</P>
<CENTER>
<BR><BR>
