</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>SafetyPosit_faq.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#E6E8FA" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/logo_and_tagline.gif">
<IMG SRC="/gifs/Line.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<H2><CENTER><STRONG>SafetyPosit - Frequently Asked Questions</STRONG></CENTER>
</H2>

<P><FONT SIZE=5>H</FONT>ere are some additional questions people have asked 
about SafetyPosit, related to 
<UL><UL><UL>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor639714">Cost justification</A>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor694276">Breaking encryption algorithms</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#anchor694501">Hot site applications</A>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor720958">Credit card numbers on the Internet</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#anchor725225">Operating Systems: future plans</A>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor727083">Worldwide applications</A>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor629821">Backing up static O/S and applications files</A>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor636350">Backup frequency</A>
</UL></UL></UL>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor639714"></A><B>Q:</B> Why should I backup my files at all? The 
price of doing so seems to represent additional cost. I'm not sure I should 
afford it now.
<P>
<B>A:</B> From 1990 to 1995, some corporations were hit hard with 
catastrophic losses due to events such as Hurricane Andrew, the Internet 
worm, the Chicago River flood, the World Trade Center bombing, the midwestern 
floods, and the Oklahoma City bombing. Less exotic, but more pervasive
occurrences, such as power outages, file loss due to error, media failure,
theft, and audit markdowns are on the rise. With current trends, the number 
of businesses affected by such things from 1995 to 2000 will be much higher. 
Couple this alarming trend with increased technology which continues to allow 
for significant increases in the volume of data which can be stored in
various forms of media storage devices. The bottom line is there is a
significant increase in the risk incurred by not backing up data, preferably 
at an offsite location.
<P>
This leads us to identify a new '80/20' rule for business, taken from a very
authoritative source: "Almost half of the enterprises that are struck by a 
business-stopping disaster never reopen and an additional 29 percent go out 
of business within two years." (Disaster Recovery Journal, Volume 8,
Issue 1, 1995) That adds up to about eighty percent. 
<!--<A HREF="http://www.drj.com/">-->
<P>
Backup costs should be compared with alternative costs associated with
recreating lost, stolen, or destroyed files. A study by International Data 
Corporation discloses that it takes an average of 19 days and costs $17,000 
to recreate just 20 megabytes of sales and marketing data. Recreating
accounting records requires an average of 21 days and $19,000. Based on these
measures, thousands of businesses lose millions of dollars of data to fire, 
power outages, equipment failures, and even operator mistakes. And today 
there are natural disasters and increasing acts of terrorism to add to the 
list.
<P>
Backups are no longer just a nice option, but an absolute requirement for
businesses to survive. And don't forget the need to please your boss, your 
management, your auditor, your Board of Directors, and your Stockholders!

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor694276"></A></A><B>Q:</B> I heard a while back about someone 
breaking the encryption method you use.

<P>
<B>A:</B> SafetyPosit incorporates an encryption method developed by RSA. 
RSA's method employs a 128-bit encryption key for use in the US and Canada, 
(subsidiaries of USA companies can get the 128-bit system outside the USA). 
In July 1995 a person in France claimed to have decrypted a single encrypted 
message. This person decrypted one eight-byte string that was buried in a large
document that was encrypted using the RC2 algorithm and a 40-bit key. The job
took 8 days using 120 workstations and two parallel supercomputers at three 
major research centers. To decrypt another message would require another 8 
days of 120 workstations and two parallel supercomputers. Remember, the 
document this guy cracked was encrypted with RSA's 40-bit technology.
<P>
Using the RC2 128-bit key would be 2^88 times harder to decrypt. This means the
computing power required to decrypt such a message would be more than 
1,000,000,000,000 (trillion) times greater than that which was used to 
decrypt the RC2 40-bit message. That is an unlikely event, to be sure! With 
foreseeable computer technology it would be practically impossible. That's 
safe! That's why we use RSA.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor694501"></A></A><B>Q:</B> What happens if I lose my main site, 
and have to recover at my backup site? 
<P>
<B>A:</B> You can always retrieve your data. There are several ways. Your 
backup site, or a hot site, must have adequate communications lines and have 
SafetyPosit configured on the computer at that site.  You then can restore as 
normal using your encryption key to decrypt the files.  If that is not
possible, we can always make a tape containing your files and send it by 
courier to wherever you would like it sent. Of course, you would still need 
your encryption key to decrypt the files.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor720958"></A></A><B>Q:</B> I know that eventually I'll be able 
to provide credit card info to you over your internet link for
payment for my backups. I am concerned about the security aspects of providing
such information that way.
<P>
<B>A:</B> Can you relate to the concept which New York Times journalist 
Peter H. Lewis presents? He says, "Sending a credit card number to an 
electronic merchant over the Internet is probably the safest way to make such 
a transaction. In the last week, for example, I handed my credit card to a
waiter who disappeared with it for five minutes. I faxed my credit card
information to a business in New Jersey, and the fax probably lay exposed to 
everyone in that office for hours and perhaps to the cleaning crew that 
night. I called a hotel and gave my card data to a reservation clerk and
continued my recklessness by ordering some merchandise from a clothing
catalogue, again by reading my credit card information to some unseen 
operator." He concludes that "compared with the risk of handing my credit 
card to a stranger, which I do nearly every day, sending it over the
Internet is pretty secure." (New York Times, 13 Nov 95, C3)
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor725225"></A></A><B>Q:</B> What operating systems and types of 
computers are supported?
<P>
<B>A:</B> SafetyPosit currently supports UNIX and Windows-NT platforms.  The 
supported UNIX platforms are Digital UNIX, HP-UX, IBM AIX, Solaris, and 
SunOS.  Windows 95 will be supported in mid-1997.  Windows 3.1, Macintosh, 
Novell, OpenVMS and others are being considered for the future. 
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor727083"></A></A><B>Q:</B> If I live outside of the US., can I 
still subscribe to the service? 
<P>
<B>A:</B> We plan to offer SafetyPosit worldwide via the Internet.  However, 
due to United States State Department regulations, we are prohibited from 
exporting SafetyPositUs RSA 128-bit key encryption outside the US and 
Canada.  Corrective legislation is pending in the US Congress.  In the 
interim, our options are to incorporate exportable 40-bit key encryption or 
allow backups without encryption.  Overseas subsidiaries of US corporations 
can obtain a waiver of the encryption export restrictions. 
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor629821"></A></A><B>Q:</B> Can I backup all of my software using 
SafetyPosit?
<P>
<B>A:</B> Yes, but SafetyPosit recommends backing up user-generated files 
first, as it is may be more economical to store backups of software programs 
on their original floppies or CD-ROM than it may be to back them up via 
SafetyPosit.  However, should you still want to pursue backing up application 
programs, etc., it can be done.  We recommend an off hour time slot, possibly 
on the weekend.  You should call us to make such arrangements.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="anchor636350"></A></A><B>Q:</B> How often should I do backups?
<P>
<B>A:</B> We recommend that backups be done daily. SafetyPosit allows you to 
set up an automatic schedule for doing daily backups automatically and 
unattended. All you need to do is leave your machine turned on.
<BR>
<BR>

<HR>
<BR><BR>

